ancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, Anglie","Of, England":"Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1210–":"omkring 1210–Afdød","1210–1294":"1210–1294","1221–Female":"1221–Afdød","1250–1294":"1250–1294","–1294":"–1294","–Female":"Afdød","1210–Female":"1210–Afdød","about 1250":"omkring 1250","25 July 1294":"25. juli 1294","1221":"1221","1210":"1210","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","about 1210":"omkring 1210","about 1221":"omkring 1221","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Of, England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1210–":"circa 1210–Overleden","1210–1294":"1210–1294","1221–Female":"1221–Overleden","1250–1294":"1250–1294","–1294":"–1294","–Female":"Overleden","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","about 1250":"circa 1250","25 July 1294":"25 juli 1294","1221":"1221","1210":"1210","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","about 1210":"circa 1210","about 1221":"circa 1221","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Of, England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1210–":"about 1210–Deceased","1210–1294":"1210–1294","1221–Female":"1221–Deceased","1250–1294":"1250–1294","–1294":"–1294","–Female":"Deceased","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","about 1250":"about 1250","25 July 1294":"25 July 1294","1221":"1221","1210":"1210","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","about 1210":"about 1210","about 1221":"about 1221","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Of, England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Diana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name borne in Roman mythology by the goddess of the moon and of hunting, equivalent to the Greek Artemis. In mythology she is characterized as both beautiful and chaste. Her name is of ancient and uncertain derivation. It probably contains a first element that is also found in the name of the Greek god <i>Dionysos</i> (  see  Dennis  ) and the Latin name of the supreme god <i>Jupiter</i>. It was adopted in Britain during the Tudor period as a learned name, a borrowing from Latin influenced by the French form   Diane .  Although it was much used by Elizabethan poets celebrating the virgin goddess and alluding to the Virgin Queen, it was not particularly popular as a given name until the end of the 19th century. In earlier centuries some clergymen were reluctant to baptize girls with this pagan name, mindful of the riots against St Paul stirred up by worshippers of Diana of the Ephesians (Acts 19:24–41). In the late 20th century, its popularity received a boost because of its association with the late  Diana , Princess of Wales (  1961–97 ), who was renowned for her beauty, glamour, and compassion."],"variants":[{"name":"Dianna","meanings":["Name borne in Roman mythology by the goddess of the moon and of hunting, equivalent to the Greek Artemis. In mythology she is characterized as both beautiful and chaste. Her name is of ancient and uncertain derivation. It probably contains a first element that is also found in the name of the Greek god <i>Dionysos</i> (  see  Dennis  ) and the Latin name of the supreme god <i>Jupiter</i>. It was adopted in Britain during the Tudor period as a learned name, a borrowing from Latin influenced by the French form   Diane .  Although it was much used by Elizabethan poets celebrating the virgin goddess and alluding to the Virgin Queen, it was not particularly popular as a given name until the end of the 19th century. In earlier centuries some clergymen were reluctant to baptize girls with this pagan name, mindful of the riots against St Paul stirred up by worshippers of Diana of the Ephesians (Acts 19:24–41). In the late 20th century, its popularity received a boost because of its association with the late  Diana , Princess of Wales (  1961–97 ), who was renowned for her beauty, glamour, and compassion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Diana was born about 1210, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Richard Fitton."},"et":{"about 1210–":"umbes 1210–Surnud","1210–1294":"1210–1294","1221–Female":"1221–Surnud","1250–1294":"1250–1294","–1294":"–1294","–Female":"Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","25 July 1294":"25 juuli 1294","1221":"1221","1210":"1210","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","about 1210":"umbes 1210","about 1221":"umbes 1221","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Of, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1210–":"noin 1210–Kuollut","1210–1294":"1210–1294","1221–Female":"1221–Kuollut","1250–1294":"1250–1294","–1294":"–1294","–Female":"Kuollut","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","about 1250":"noin 1250","25 July 1294":"25. heinäkuuta 1294","1221":"1221","1210":"1210","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","about 1210":"noin 1210","about 1221":"noin 1221","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Of, England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1210–":"environ 1210–Décédée","1210–1294":"1210–1294","1221–Female":"1221–Décédée","1250–1294":"1250–1294","–1294":"–1294","–Female":"Décédée","1210–Female":"1210–Décédée","about 1250":"environ 1250","25 July 1294":"25 juillet 1294","1221":"1221","1210":"1210","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","about 1210":"environ 1210","about 1221":"environ 1221","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, Angleterre","Of, England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Diana est née environ 1210, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils et 3 filles avec Richard Fitton."},"de":{"about 1210–":"um 1210–Verstorben","1210–1294":"1210–1294","1221–Female":"1221–Verstorben","1250–1294":"1250–1294","–1294":"–1294","–Female":"Verstorben","1210–Female":"1210–Verstorben","about 1250":"um 1250","25 July 1294":"25. Juli 1294","1221":"1221","1210":"1210","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","about 1210":"um 1210","about 1221":"um 1221","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Of, England":"Engl